                </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="alert alert-success" id="recent-changes">
                <h3 style="margin-top: 0;">📝 Recent Changes (v1.00 - Jan 8, 2026)</h3>
                <ul style="margin: 5px 0 0 20px;">
                    <li><strong>Media.pm Addition:</strong> New DBIx::Class Result model for managing media files and assets</li>
                    <li><strong>Initial Documentation:</strong> Created comprehensive documentation for schema, types, and file management</li>
                    <li><strong>Content Association:</strong> Documented optional relationship to Content model for media grouping</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <section id="overview">
                <h2>Overview</h2>
                <p>
                    The <strong>Media</strong> model (Comserv/lib/Comserv/Model/Schema/Ency/Result/Media.pm) 
                    provides a database abstraction layer for managing media files, assets, and attachments across the Comserv application. 
                    It is a DBIx::Class Result class that supports:
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Media file metadata storage (filename, type, references)</li>
                    <li>File type classification and filtering</li>
                    <li>Optional content association (grouping media by content)</li>
                    <li>Media lifecycle management (creation, deletion, reference counting)</li>
                    <li>Support for images, documents, videos, audio, and custom media types</li>
                    <li>Flexible filtering by file type or content relationship</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                    Media acts as a registry for files in the application, storing metadata that allows 
                    controllers and utilities to manage files, enforce access control, track file usage, and 
                    maintain relationships between media and content (articles, documentation, projects, etc.).
                </p>
            </section>

            <section id="schema">
                <h2>Database Schema & Fields</h2>
                
                <h3>Table: media</h3>
                <p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Store metadata and references for media files and assets</p>
                
                <table class="table table-bordered">
                    <tr>
                        <th>Field Name</th>
                        <th>Data Type</th>
                        <th>Nullable</th>
                        <th>Default</th>
                        <th>Description</th>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td><code>id</code></td>
                        <td>INTEGER</td>
                        <td>No</td>
                        <td>Auto-increment</td>
                        <td>Primary key - unique media record identifier</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td><code>filename</code></td>
                        <td>VARCHAR(255)</td>
                        <td>No</td>
                        <td>—</td>
                        <td>Original filename (e.g., document.pdf, photo.jpg, slide_deck.pptx)</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td><code>type</code></td>
                        <td>VARCHAR(50)</td>
                        <td>No</td>
                        <td>—</td>
                        <td>File type/MIME classification (e.g., image, document, video, audio, application)</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td><code>content_id</code></td>
                        <td>INTEGER</td>
                        <td>Yes</td>
                        <td>NULL</td>
                        <td>Foreign key to content.id (optional; allows grouping media by content)</td>
                    </tr>
                </table>

                <h3>Field Details</h3>
                
                <h4>filename</h4>
                <p>
                    The original filename as uploaded or created. Examples:
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li><code>comserv_logo.png</code></li>
                    <li><code>deployment_guide_v2.1.pdf</code></li>
                    <li><code>product_demo_20260108.mp4</code></li>
                    <li><code>infrastructure_diagram.svg</code></li>
                </ul>
                <p><strong>Note:</strong> Filesystem path not stored here (handled by file management utility); only filename for display.</p>

                <h4>type</h4>
                <p>
                    Categorizes the media file for filtering and validation. Recommended values:
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li><code>image</code> - JPEG, PNG, GIF, SVG, WebP</li>
                    <li><code>document</code> - PDF, Word, Excel, PowerPoint</li>
                    <li><code>video</code> - MP4, WebM, MOV, AVI</li>
                    <li><code>audio</code> - MP3, WAV, OGG, AAC</li>
                    <li><code>application</code> - ZIP, EXE, JAR, Executable archives</li>
                    <li><code>text</code> - TXT, CSV, Log files</li>
                    <li><code>source</code> - Code files (Perl, Python, JS, etc.)</li>
                </ul>
                <p><strong>Best Practice:</strong> Use consistent type values for queries and filtering.</p>

                <h4>content_id</h4>
                <p>
                    Optional foreign key linking media to Content records. Enables:
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Media Grouping:</strong> Associate multiple images/files with a single content item</li>
                    <li><strong>Cascade Operations:</strong> Delete all media when associated content is removed</li>
                    <li><strong>Usage Tracking:</strong> Know which content uses which media</li>
                    <li><strong>NULL for Orphaned Media:</strong> Media not yet associated with any content</li>
                </ul>
                <p><strong>LEFT JOIN Logic:</strong> Relationship uses LEFT JOIN, allowing orphaned media records.</p>
            </section>

            <section id="relationships">
                <h2>Relationships</h2>
                
                <h3>belongs_to: content</h3>
                <pre><code>$media->content();  # Returns Content object if content_id is set
my $parent_content = $media->content();
if ($parent_content) {
    print "Media belongs to: " . $parent_content->title . "\n";
}</code></pre>
                <p><strong>Relationship Type:</strong> belongs_to (LEFT JOIN)</p>
                <p><strong>Foreign Key:</strong> content_id → content.id</p>
                <p><strong>Nullable:</strong> YES (NULL if media not associated with content)</p>
                <p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Link media files to their parent content item</p>
                <p><strong>Join Type:</strong> LEFT (allows orphaned media without parent content)</p>

                <h3>Recommended Inverse Relationship</h3>
                <p>The Content model should define:</p>
                <pre><code>$content->media();  # Get all media associated with this content
my @files = $content->media()->all;
print "Content has " . scalar(@files) . " files\n";</code></pre>
                <p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Enable queries like "all images for article X" or "media by content type"</p>
            </section>

            <section id="supported-types">
                <h2>Supported Media Types</h2>
                
                <h3>Type Classification</h3>
                <p>
                    The <code>type</code> field categorizes files for application-level filtering and validation:
                </p>
                <table class="table table-bordered">
                    <tr>
                        <th>Type Value</th>
                        <th>File Extensions</th>
                        <th>MIME Types</th>
                        <th>Use Cases</th>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td><code>image</code></td>
                        <td>.jpg, .png, .gif, .svg, .webp</td>
                        <td>image/jpeg, image/png, image/svg+xml</td>
                        <td>UI graphics, photos, diagrams, logos</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td><code>document</code></td>
                        <td>.pdf, .docx, .xlsx, .pptx</td>
                        <td>application/pdf, application/msword</td>
                        <td>Guides, reports, proposals, templates</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td><code>video</code></td>
                        <td>.mp4, .webm, .mov, .avi</td>
                        <td>video/mp4, video/webm</td>
                        <td>Demos, tutorials, presentations</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td><code>audio</code></td>
                        <td>.mp3, .wav, .ogg, .aac</td>
                        <td>audio/mpeg, audio/wav</td>
                        <td>Podcasts, narration, sound effects</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td><code>application</code></td>
                        <td>.zip, .tar, .exe, .jar</td>
                        <td>application/zip, application/x-executable</td>
                        <td>Releases, installers, archives</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td><code>text</code></td>
                        <td>.txt, .csv, .log</td>
                        <td>text/plain, text/csv</td>
                        <td>Data exports, logs, raw text</td>
                    </tr>
                </table>

                <h3>Custom Type Registration</h3>
                <p>
                    Applications can define additional type values in configuration:
                </p>
                <pre><code>
# Custom type example
my $media = $rs->create({
    filename   => 'backup_20260108.sql',
    type       => 'database',  # Custom type
    content_id => undef,
});
                </code></pre>
                <p><strong>Note:</strong> Use consistent type values across application; consider documenting in app configuration.</p>
            </section>

            <section id="api-methods">
                <h2>API Methods</h2>
                
                <h3>Instance Methods</h3>
                
                <h4>$media->content()</h4>
                <pre><code>my $parent = $media->content();
if ($parent) {
    print "Associated with: " . $parent->id . "\n";
} else {
    print "Media is orphaned (no parent content)\n";
}</code></pre>
                <p><strong>Returns:</strong> Content Result object, or undef if content_id is NULL</p>
                <p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Get parent content for this media file</p>

                <h3>Standard DBIx::Class Methods</h3>
                <pre><code>
# Create media record
my $media = $rs->create({
    filename   => 'photo.jpg',
    type       => 'image',
    content_id => $content_id,  # Optional
});

# Update media type
$media->type('document');
$media->update();

# Delete media
$media->delete();

# Search by type
my @images = $rs->search({ type => 'image' })->all;

# Search by content
my @content_media = $rs->search({ content_id => $id })->all;

# Search with content prefetch
my @with_parent = $rs->search(
    { type => 'image' },
    { prefetch => 'content' }
)->all;
                </code></pre>
            </section>

            <section id="examples">
                <h2>Usage Examples</h2>
                
                <h3>Example 1: Register Uploaded Image</h3>
                <pre><code>
my $schema = $c->model('Ency::Schema');
my $rs = $schema->resultset('Media');

my $media = $rs->create({
    filename   => 'documentation_screenshot.png',
    type       => 'image',
    content_id => $article_id,
});

print "Registered media ID: " . $media->id . "\n";
                </code></pre>

                <h3>Example 2: List All Images for Content</h3>
                <pre><code>
my @images = $rs->search({
    type       => 'image',
    content_id => $article_id,
})->all;

foreach my $img (@images) {
    print $img->filename . " (ID: " . $img->id . ")\n";
}
                </code></pre>

                <h3>Example 3: Find Orphaned Media</h3>
                <pre><code>
my @orphaned = $rs->search({
    content_id => undef
})->all;

print "Found " . scalar(@orphaned) . " orphaned media files\n";
                </code></pre>

                <h3>Example 4: Bulk Type Update</h3>
                <pre><code>
my @old_videos = $rs->search({ type => 'video' })->all;

foreach my $v (@old_videos) {
    $v->type('multimedia');
    $v->update();
}

print "Updated " . scalar(@old_videos) . " videos to 'multimedia'\n";
                </code></pre>

                <h3>Example 5: Media with Parent Content Info</h3>
                <pre><code>
my @docs = $rs->search(
    { type => 'document' },
    { prefetch => 'content' }
)->all;

foreach my $doc (@docs) {
    print $doc->filename . " → ";
    if ($doc->content) {
        print "Used in content ID " . $doc->content->id . "\n";
    } else {
        print "Unassociated\n";
    }
}
                </code></pre>
            </section>

            <section id="troubleshooting">
                <h2>Troubleshooting</h2>
                
                <h3>Issue: "Can't find Content with id X" on content lookup</h3>
                <p><strong>Cause:</strong> content_id references a Content record that no longer exists.</p>
                <p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Set content_id to NULL (orphan the media): `$media->content_id(undef)->update()`</li>
                    <li>Or delete the media: `$media->delete()`</li>
                    <li>Check database for orphaned records: `SELECT id FROM media WHERE content_id NOT IN (SELECT id FROM content)`</li>
                </ul>

                <h3>Issue: "Type field too restrictive"</h3>
                <p><strong>Cause:</strong> VARCHAR(50) insufficient for long type values or custom naming.</p>
                <p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Use standardized short type values (image, document, etc.)</li>
                    <li>Store detailed description elsewhere (in filename, notes, separate field)</li>
                    <li>Expand column if needed: `ALTER TABLE media MODIFY COLUMN type VARCHAR(100)`</li>
                </ul>

                <h3>Issue: "Duplicate filename references"</h3>
                <p><strong>Cause:</strong> No unique constraint on filename (same file registered multiple times).</p>
                <p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Check for duplicates: `SELECT filename, COUNT(*) FROM media GROUP BY filename HAVING COUNT(*) > 1`</li>
                    <li>Consolidate if possible (merge duplicate references)</li>
                    <li>Add unique constraint if needed: `ALTER TABLE media ADD UNIQUE INDEX idx_filename (filename)`</li>
                </ul>

                <h3>Issue: "Media not showing up in content queries"</h3>
                <p><strong>Cause:</strong> Forgot to prefetch 'content' relationship in search.</p>
                <p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Use prefetch in query: `search({...}, { prefetch => 'content' })`</li>
                    <li>Or call ->content() explicitly (lazy-loads relationship)</li>
                    <li>Check content_id is not NULL and points to valid Content record</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

